The deadline to complete the 2020 Census is Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2020.

We know that COVID-19 has impacted each of the commonwealth’s communities - especially our education communities, but challenges like those we are facing as a result of the pandemic, make an accurate count even more critical. Each year PA communities receive $26.8 billion in federal funding that goes toward education, healthcare, housing, food assistance, and more. To support our communities, we need everyone living in Forest County to be counted.

https://www.pa.gov/census/

post_text: Emily Everett, a Slippery Rock Communication major and Emma Cussins, a Clarion University Special Education major, participated in internships through Northwest PA Job Connect (NWPA) at Forest Area School District this summer. Ms. Cussins interned in the Special Education Department, while Ms. Everett interned with the Curriculum and Technology Department. The students worked with the administration on procedures and projects to address needs due to the Covid 19 pandemic and to prepare for the start of the school year. Ms. Cussins worked on setting up transition assessments so that students could access these forms online and Ms. Everett worked on website development, publications, and setting up an e-mentoring program for businesses and high school students to share information about careers virtually.

post_text: The Forest Area School District will be offering a summer drama/music enrichment program. This program will follow all of the procedures passed in the Board of Directors reopening plan. The program will run every Wednesday, from July 22nd until August 19th. Mrs. Beatty and Mr. Wortman will be at West Forest from 9:30 AM until 11:00 AM, and then East Forest from noon until 1:30 PM. If you would like to register and have not already, please call Central Office at 1-814-755-4491. There will be four weeks of rehearsal and then a video of student work compiled during the fifth and final week. Please reach out to Mr. Wortman or Mrs. Beatty with any questions or concerns.

post_text: In February 2020, the Forest Area School District and Forest Warren Mental Wellness Association were awarded a grant of $7,875.00 from the J. Bowman Proper Charitable Trust. The purpose of this grant is to educate youth on the value of growing your own food, and the importance of healthy eating for many generations to come. The grant provided a greenhouse to East Forest School in Marienville, PA. Students will learn how to grow plants for the Marienville Community Garden utilizing the new greenhouse. Students will be educated in practical skills they can transfer to be used at home and entrepreneurial skills for their future.

post_text:
The Warren Forest Counties Economic Opportunity Council was awarded a Community Services Block Grant Discretionary Grant from the Pennsylvania Department of Community and Economic Development. The intent of the Grant was to address the immediate needs of the residents of Forest and Warren County caused by the onset of the COVID – 19 Pandemic. The Agency determined that providing access to nutritional meals and food was the most pressing need. In response, the Agency provided the Forest County Commissioners $7,850 to purchase and distribute food within the County.

Recognizing that the need for nutritional food is and will continue to be an issue, the Agency is partnering with the Forest Area School District to expand the District’s Community Gardens. Located in Marienville and soon in Tionesta, the Gardens will allow local residents the ability to grow their own food. Hopefully benefiting the Community aesthetically and nutritionally.

As summer is now in full swing, we would like to announce that Tuesday June 30, will be the last day for our free meal program due to declining participation. We understand that many of you have received a p-EBT card for the purchase of groceries over the summer. If you have not received one yet, please watch for it! These cards are intended to help parents with meals for students throughout the summer and should be awarded to all Forest Area students as a result of our enrollment in the CEP program.

Meals will be available Tuesday, June 30 at the East Forest School, Farm Fresh Foods, County Line Market, the Endeavor Community Center, and the President fire hall.

The District would like to thank our volunteers, cafeteria staff, van drivers, and the business owners who permitted us to use their locations for distribution. Without your dedication, the great success of this program would not have been possible.

post_text: This past February, Mr. Hale's Fourth Grade class had two presenters visit and discuss the effects of Lyme Disease. The students were given the opportunity to create a poster for an art contest conducted by the PA Department of Health. The theme was "Don't Let a Tick Make You Sick". Entries were submitted by students all over Pennsylvania. We are proud to announce that Nora Lesko won third place for her poster in the Third and Fourth Grade group! Way to go Nora!

West Forest 2020 Co-Salutatorian ~ Telford Kunselman III

TJ is the son of Telford and Julie Kunselman.

While at West Forest, he participated in basketball and golf, in which he earned MVP his senior year. His clubs included National Honors Society, Student Council (Treasurer), FCCLA (Vice President), Student Historians, Fitness Club, Foreign Language Club, Varsity Club, and Robotics. He is also the Secretary of the Class of 2020.

TJ has been awarded the Ruth and Vernon Taylor Salutatorian Award, Presidential Excellence Gold Award, Penn State Behrend Chancellor’s Scholarship, and has been accepted into the Penn State Behrend Honors Program and STEM Leaders Program. His future plans include attending Penn State Behrend, where he will pursue a degree in engineering.

West Forest 2020 Co-Salutatorian ~ Noah Burke

Noah is the son of John and Stacy Burke. He has three sisters, Sarah, Annah, and Avah.

While at West Forest, he participated in soccer, basketball, and baseball. His clubs included National Honors Society, Varsity Club, Yearbook, and Fitness Club. He is also a member of 4-H.

Noah has been awarded the Ruth and Vernon Taylor Salutatorian Award, the Presidential Excellence Gold Award, the Soccer Scholarship, Sports Boosters Scholarship, Athlete of the Year, the Lions Club Vocational Scholarship, the Kinnear Scholarship, and Penn Tech’s Earth and Space Science Scholarship.

His future plans include attending the Pennsylvania College of Technology, to become a Heavy Equipment Operator, and eventually starting his own excavation business.

Thank You from Forest Area School District

The administration, faculty, and staff want to say thank you to everyone who supported us during the COVID-19 quarantine. We appreciate the awesome job parents did getting their children to classes whether they were online or the phone. The parents also figured out technology, daily assignments and supported our teachers through the development of this “new normal”. Our students were the best! They showed up daily in the classroom meets and worked diligently on their assignments. We greatly appreciate everyone who participated in our community of learning!

post_text:
3rd Annual Talk to Your State Senator Video Contest

For the past three years, Mrs. Hartle and Mr. Wortman have worked with students to enter the "Talk to your State Senator" video contest. The theme for this year's contest was Preserving Pennsylvania's Legacy, with an emphasis on farming.

Once again, our middle and high school groups won the senate district! Both groups will advance to the state level of competition and compete for scholarship money. The winners will be announced this summer.

The senior high group consisted of Hunter Turba, Liam Dickson, Waylin Dashner, Brett Banks, and Sebastian Campbell.

The middle school group consisted of Izzy Flick, Hailey Greenlee, Jessica Culver, Katie Salsgiver, and Tori Brown.

Congratulations!

Boys video link:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1dhSCSJZYHPRc37-2jQiJ6-6-q2V9tuDR/view?ts=5eab0d93

Girls video link:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/16Zr-0zo_9efSoUzayYF83W2fiaIyYH9p/view?ts=5eab0dc4

Good afternoon Forest Area families, the East and West Forest Student Council’s would like to host a Virtual Spirit Week starting next week, and would love your participation.

Monday, April 6th, is Outdoor Day. Share a picture of yourself or your family doing something outdoors.

Tuesday, April 7th, is Pet Day. Post a picture of yourself with your pets.

Wednesday, April 8th, is Photogenic Day. Share a picture of yourself in a unique spot where you plan to do your school work.

Thursday, April 9th, is Creative Cuisine Day. Post a picture of yourself with a creative food dish that you have made.

Friday, April 10th, is School Color Wars. Share a picture of yourself in either Black and Orange, for East Forest students, or Blue and Gold, for West Forest students.

Pictures can be shared on our Facebook page.

We hope you are all staying safe and active. We miss you, and we look forward to moving forward with your education in the very near future.

post_text: As you may have already heard, Governor Wolf called for the close of all schools in PA for 10 business days, effective Monday, March 16, 2020. This shut down is for students and families to practice social isolation and stay away from places where there will be large groups of people. There will be no practices, athletic events, trips, school activities or any other use of the buildings. Tentatively, school is scheduled to resume on March 31, 2020, however, this is a quickly changing situation. We will call with any updated or additional information as it becomes available.

What is the 2020 Census? As mandated by the U.S. Constitution, it is a once-every-decade count of everyone living in the country. Knowing the number of people in your community helps inform how billions in federal funding is distributed annually for public services like clinics, schools, and hundreds of programs. The census also determines how the seats in Congress are allocated. Starting in March of 2020, you can respond online, by phone, or by mail.
Shape your future. START HERE. Visit 2020census.gov.

post_text:
West Forest Sixth Graders Study Cells

Mrs. Druckemiller’s sixth grade science classes have been working very hard to learn about life’s classification and structure. The students have learned how living things are classified, what are prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells, various cell parts and their jobs, and other important concepts throughout the chapter. The students were asked to make either a 3D plant or animal cell to end the chapter. They could use edible or nonedible materials and had to label the cell parts. As you can see the students, greatly enjoyed this project and were very creative in their designs! Great job sixth grade!

Photo 1:
Back: Eric Peyatt, Conner Summerville, Brayden Felix, Grace Flick, Alexis Donato, Becca Wagner
Front: Miguel Martinez, Christian Kluck, Ezra Busch, Kylian Droddy, Tyler Swaim

Photo 2:
Back: Hazel Hilyer, Trevor Kuntz, Zachary Wild, Nate Sample, Ayzlynn Nelson
Front: Macalie Hoffman, Gabe Chambers, Jacob Naser, Ayla Reese, Lilly Corfield

post_text:
This past fall, students in 3rd grade at East Forest made cards for a soldier stationed in the Middle East. The soldier is SRA Anthony Fetzer. He is the uncle of one of the students in the class, Willow Walker. On February 11, SRA Fetzer made a surprise visit to the classroom to thank the students for their cards. Willow didn’t know that he was back home, and he was able to have a very heartwarming surprise reunion with her. Afterwards, he spent some time visiting with the class and showing some items from the culture in the Middle East.
He is the uncle of one of the students in the class, Willow Walker. On February 11, SRA Fetzer made a surprise visit to the classroom to thank the students for their cards. Willow didn’t know that he was back home, and he was able to have a very heartwarming surprise reunion with her. SRA Fetzer then spent time visiting with the class discussing the culture and showing them items from the Middle East.

“Purple Outage” at Forest Area Basketball Game

The Mighty Mini’s Relay Team and FCCLA are proud to announce a “Purple Outage” at East Forest on Monday, January 13th, with proceeds from the evening being donated to the American Cancer Society. The boys’ basketball team will be hosting the Cranberry boys team with the junior varsity game beginning at 6:00 and varsity to follow. There will be a concession stand, basket raffles, and information available on the American Cancer Society’s Relay for Life. Purple is the color of Relay for Life, which represents all types of cancer. Purple symbolizes hope. We hope you can join us in an evening of entertainment by wearing purple and cheering on the Forest Area Boys Basketball team while supporting a worthy cause.

What is the 2020 Census? As mandated by the U.S. Constitution, it is a once-every-decade count of everyone living in the country. Knowing the number of people in your community helps inform how billions in federal funding is distributed annually for public services like clinics, schools, and hundreds of programs. The census also determines how the seats in Congress are allocated. Starting in March of 2020, you can respond online, by phone, or by mail.
Shape your future. START HERE. Visit 2020census.gov.

post_text:
The Mussel Man Returns To West Forest Elementary

On Wednesday, December 4, Philip Mathias visited Mr. Hale’s Trout Crew. He explained how his company removed thousands of mussels prior to the construction of the new Hunter Station Bridge. His presentation showed the life cycle of the mussels in the Allegheny River. The students learned that the larvae of mussels use fish as hosts, including trout. Each student was able to inspect various types of mussels. Thank you to East Forest Principal, Deb Arner, for making our shirts.

Photo Identification:

Front Row (L-R): Morgan, Kiarra, Nora, Giannah, Izabella, Kayley
Back Row (L-R): Philip Mathias, Brayden, Cameron, Devious, Gabe, Nick, Ryan, Mr. Hale

International Hour of Code
We live in a world surrounded by technology. And we know that whatever field our students choose to go into as adults, their ability to succeed will increasingly depend on understanding how technology works.

That’s why Forest Area School District is joining in on the largest learning event in history: The Hour of Code, during Computer Science Education Week (December 9-15). More than 100 million students worldwide have already tried an Hour of Code. Our Hour of Code is making a statement that Forest Area School District is ready to teach these foundational 21st-century skills.

Pictured is West Forest 7th grader Izek Sample. Since Monday, he has coded over 100 lines of code.

Additional photos include 9th graders:
Left to right: Emmalee Gray, Jade Gilbert, Ryah McWilliams

Front to back: Nautica Sharp, Madison Borowski

post_text: Nine West Forest Elementary students in fifth grade were selected by the Young Writer’s Association for publication in Spooky Sagas 2019 - From the Shadows. Students were asked to write a short story (a spooky saga) consisting of one hundred words or less, in order to be eligible for a nationwide writing contest for young writers. The contest was well received and over 10,000 entries were received by the deadline of November 1. These students from West Forest Elementary were chosen and will have their stories published. Not only will West Forest Elementary receive a copy of the book, but also a copy will be sent to The Library of Congress in Washington DC. What an outstanding achievement for these young writers!

Forest Area School District and Pennsylvania Department of Transportation are reminding everyone the winter season is again approaching. With combined efforts the Department, School District, school bus drivers and the motoring public, we can all achieve a successful and safe winter season.

Some winter safety tips to following before driving on winter roads are:

Keep the vehicle in good condition by prepping the vehicle for winter.
*Check wiper blades and replace if needed and keep wiper fluid tank filled with appropriate fluid rated at -30 degrees.
*Check Battery.
*Check the cooling system is in working order.
*Check tire pressure and tread levels. Replace tires if tread level is less than 2/32 of an inch.

post_text:
Forest Area School District, in partnership with Sandy Hook Promise, a national, nonprofit organization led by several family members whose loved ones were killed in the tragic mass shooting at Sandy Hook Elementary School, took part in Start With Hello Week during the week of September 23- 27. Start with Hello teaches students how to reach out to and include those who may be socially isolated as well as to create a culture of inclusion and connectedness within their school or youth organization. Start With Hello Week raises awareness and educates students, brings attention to the growing epidemic of social isolation in our schools and communities while empowering them to help change the culture. At East Forest Elementary/Jr. Sr. High School, students participated in various activities such as a New Student Spotlight Board, Mix It Up/No One Eats Alone Lunch, Greetings In a Different Language, and a Human Scavenger Hunt to promote connectedness and inclusion.
The picture is of the new student board with pictures of their new East Forest Friends. Picture:Adrianna Clark

Forest Area School District is pleased to announce that we have qualified for the Community Eligibility Program through our child nutrition program for both East Forest and West Forest Schools. All PK-12 students in the District will receive free breakfast and lunch every day. Students and families will still be responsible for the purchase of any a la carte items that students choose to supplement their meal.

Both East and West Forest Schools will continue to offer the after school food program, which is free for all students grades PK-12, so students may also receive a snack or dinner at the end of the day prior to going home or participating in sports or other after school activities. This program is free of charge to all students.

Parents are reminded that they can access lunch menus and their student’s account information at SchoolCafe.com. Deposits of $50 or more receive a discount which should cover the cost of the fee charged for paying with a credit card.

The first day of fall athletic practices is tomorrow, Monday, August 12. Boys and girls varsity soccer and volleyball will practice from 8:00-10:00 AM at West Forest High School. Practice will alternate between East and West Forest each day and the activity bus will leave at 7:15 AM. Currently, the scheduled stops are East Forest, The Sawmill, Fox's Pizza (in Tylersburg), North Clarion, the Visitor Center, and West Forest. All athletes must have a PIAA physical form completed and turned in before they are allowed to practice.

Junior high soccer and junior high golf will begin after school starts.

Varsity golf will begin August 14 at Hunter's Station at 3:00.

If you have any questions, please call West Forest School at 814-755-3302 or East Forest School at 927-6688.

post_text:
East Forest Mini Relay Event

The Mini Relay for Life Club at East Forest High School recently held a relay event for the elementary students on the soccer field. The children were separated into four groups that walked around the loop like you would do at an actual relay. As they walked the older students taught them topics such as sun safety and exercise benefits which will help keep them healthy as they grow into adulthood. A hydration table was available including a bead station. As each lap was made a bead was issued. Students were able to get lap sponsors for a monetary donation. All proceeds from the day were given to the American Cancer Society's Forest County Relay for Life.

The second graders of West Forest Elementary were treated to an assembly of pedal bikes. Each child was fitted with a helmet which he/she will keep. After the fitting, each child had the chance to ride a pedal bike around a mapped out bike course. The course was patrolled by Americorp workers who would teach the students about different road sign. The students entered the roadway by first stopping to look for oncoming bikes, they proceeded to the yield sign and merged onto the trail. The roadway had signs for hospitals, slippery roads, hills, turns and one way. Although the weather was wet and rainy the students and workers were bright and sunny. (2nd Grade Teacher - Erin Brannon)

Jarrett Michael Kahle - East Forest Salutatorian

Jarrett Kahle is the son of Penny and Tom Kahle. Jarrett has participated in Bible Club, National Honor Society, and Student Council. He also played varsity soccer, basketball, and track earning the Male Athlete of the Year his sophomore year and the Sportsmanship Award his junior year. This year he was awarded the Forest Fires Soccer Scholarship and the Marienville Volunteer Fire Company Scholarship. He plans to attend Grove City College to study social work, but most importantly he plans on being a light for Jesus Christ.

Musical Instrument Donations Needed

The Forest Area School District is requesting and accepting any donations of musical instruments. Cost of renting or purchasing an instrument is a hardship for many families. We are trying to ease that burden while growing our music program. If anyone would like to donate an instrument, even if it is need of repair, please contact Mr. Brian Rosen or Mrs. Lori Beatty at West Forest High School (755-3611) or East Forest High School (927-6688).

Pictured (left to right): Fifth graders: Grace Flick (trombone), Macalie Hoffman (french horn), Mr. Brian Rosen (music teacher for 35 years in the Forest Area School District) and Ezra Bush (percussion).

post_text: Forest County was represented at the 2019 PA Envirothon by five students from West Forest Secondary. These students had a primary goal of improving the Oral Component Score. This has been a challenge for our students in the past. They had one week to prepare a response to a scenario that was released the Monday before the competition. They worked on the response, and we are proud to say the score was double the last year's score! They walked out with smiles on their faces. This was a win for us, as we had many challenges through the year, getting the entire team in one place to do any training for the events. If you see, Chris Pedersen, Dominic Grubbs, Belle Ralston, Morgan Miller or Dan Schwab, please tell them thank you for representing The Forest!

post_text:
Stanley Returns

Aaliyah Donato sent Stanley to shadow the Tionesta Ambulance crew. He spent a week with Britney Donato and Butch Johnston at the Tionesta Ambulance. While he was there, he went to many places in Tionesta. He stopped by to see the sheriff, a policeman, the Courtroom and a jail cell. They also took Stanley to the Fire Department where he was able to sit in the fire trucks. Britney and Butch then brought Stanley back to school and talked to the students about Stanley's adventures in Tionesta.

Genesee Phillips sent Stanley to Columbia, Kentucky. The family was having such a good time with Stanley that they kept him a few extra days. While he was in Kentucky, he attended church services, camped with the boys scouts, and watched softball and baseball games. His favorite thing to do was to play tag with the kids.

Natalie Wagner sent Stanley to Florida to see a family friend. Stanley is enjoying the nice weather and is refusing to come north.

Samantha Payne sent Stanley to Chicago. He is having so much fun that he does not want to return to school. He may stay for the summer.

Welding Students Earn Certification

Two East Forest students received certificates in the evening welding technology program at Venango Technology Center.

The students are Lukas Slosser, and Danial Ruhman. The program was coordinated among VTC, the Keystone Community Education Council and Community College of Allegheny County.

Students earned welding certifications as well as 18 college credits from CCAC. There were 57 welding credentials earned, with nine students earning multiple credentials.

All students also received Occupational Safety and Health Administration certification, as well as training in operating a forklift.

Students will receive their official certificates from CCAC in June.

On May 17, members of the East Forest English Literature and Interpretation class attended a performance of "Murikamification" by the Dutch performance group Arch8. Creator Erik Kaiel used the literature of Japanese author Haruki Murikami, who was read and studied in class, as inspiration for "Murikamification." During the performance, which ranged throughout Pittsburgh's cultural district, the students experienced the weirdness and surrealism found in Murakami's work through a combination of modern dance, acrobatics, theater, and parkour. After the performace the group dined at Kiku, a Japanese restaurant, and toured the University of Pittsburgh.

Group Picture: From left, Cameron Whisner, Tessa Korchak, Taylor Andrews, Tyler Bowen, Arch8 choreographer Erik Kaiel, and Jimmy Porterfield.

Kaiel and Porterfield: Arch8 choreographer and performer Erik Kaiel holds Jimmy Porterfield off the ground for a picture.

Teams of students from West Forest’s 7th and 8th grade competed in the Komatsu Fluid Power Challenge on Tuesday, May 14, 2019, at the Rocky Grove Firehall. Their job was to build a machine that would be powered by syringes filled with water or air. This machine had to be able to pick up a wooden dowel, rotate it, and then place it down on a board that was labeled with different point values. This was the first year that West Forest competed in this competition. It was a great experience and we look forward to next year!

Pictured: Jordan Kostenbauder, Colton Kuntz, Mason Hooper, Colleana Tirado, Gunnar Hasychak, Jeffrey Bayle, Ty Brown

10 years and counting...
On May 3, 2019 the West Forest Elementary Starfish Club held their tenth annual carnival. The theme this year was BIG 10 Sports. The children played basketball, football, golf, and many other sports related activities. They had the opportunity to compete in a free though contest that was won by Devious Hipple. They danced with the Lion's Club Lion and jumped in the bouncy house all night long.
We would like to thank all the community organizations that attended. We hit a new record this year with 27 activities for the children. Maybe next year, we can hit 30. We would also like to thank our PTO for a $500.00 donation and Muccio Transportation for a $300.00 donations. These funds were used to pay for two inflatables. We also received $250 from Fryburg Sportsmen's Club and $100 from Central Electric. Without the support of our community, we could not provide the carnival and many other wonderful experiences for the students of Forest County.

post_text:
In March, West Forest Elementary students had a guest author visit. The local author, Gina Burris, wrote Tallulah's Diner. It is an adorable story about the river animals of the Allegheny. During her visit, Gina talked about the writing process with the students in grades 3-6. She shared some of her tips for being a great writer. After the visit, the students competed in a writing contest where they had to pretend to be a river animal that was going to Tallulah's Diner to share a story about what makes them unique and special. All of the students' stories were fun to read. They showed imagination and creativity, but nine students were chosen to receive prizes in the contest.

Photo: front Row - Tara Brown (Librarian's choice), Nora Lesko (3rd grade teacher's Choice), Abbi Bell (4th grade teacher's choice), Izzy Wagner (Principal's Choice)

Back row - Harley Ellenberger (6th grade teacher's choice), Patrick Ross (Most Creative), Christian Kluck (5th grade teacher's choice), Alya Reese (5th grade teacher's choice), Jayden McKeel (Best in Show)

post_text:
EAST FOREST
During a social studies lesson on current events, Mrs. Preisel’s students at East Forest became increasingly interested in the proposed wall to border Mexico and the United States. Students began researching to have an informed opinion from several sources and then constructed a persuasive essay on whether or not they thought the wall is necessary.

Mr.Hartwig, East Forest's high school history teacher, came in to speak and answer questions. Students asked, “Why do we have walls? Walls in our homes, schools, etc.?” Mr. Hartwig addressed both sides of the issue. Also, he stressed the importance of people that move to this country need to believe in our ethics our form of government.

“Why are they building the wall?”, one student asked. Mr. Hartwig replied that it is important to check people coming into the country. He emphasized how important compromise is and that our country has always strived to lift people up!

FCCLA will be sponsoring the annual "Cutest Contests" at the Elementary Carnival which will be held at the West Forest School on Friday, May 3 at 6:00 pm. One contest will be for Forest County's Cutest Baby. Any child who is age 2 or younger can be entered by submitting a picture of the child to the West Forest High School Office. Please put the child's name, parent's name and phone number on the back of the photo. If you would like the photo returned, please also note that on the back. The second contest is for Forest County's Cutest Pet. The same procedure of picture submission will be used for this contest. Contestants will be voted for during the carnival by placing money into the various containers. The baby or pet receiving the most money will be declared the winner and the picture will be published in the Forest Press and be given a $10 gift certificate. All profits will help the FCCLA National Team go to the National Leadership Conference in Anaheim, CA this summer.

Pictured below: Belle Ralston and her puppy, Ivy

On April 22, 2019 the 3rd and 9th grades students at West Forest School had a guest speaker visit their classes. Mr. Daniel Dunkel of Green Line Polymers in Shippenville, Pennsylvania explained the process of recycling plastics into heavy pipes. The students learned that some types of plastics can be recycled easily and others are harder to use again, but all should be turned in for recycling. Now they will be using what they have learned to create bouncy balls from different polymers and testing them to see which type works the best.

Back Row: 9th grade students
Middle and Front row: 3rd grade students
Guest Speaker: Mr. Daniel Dunkel

The Husky Dog Pound competition is a Shark Tank like competition. The students named their product Flat-Hesive, hot glue sheets that would be used on larger objects.

From left to right: Nic Gigliotti, Andrew Dando, TJ Kunselman, Elliot Eisenman, and Ethan McWilliams

post_text: Three East Forest FCCLA students were recognized at the State Leadership Conference held in Seven Springs from March 20 – 22, 2019. These students were recognized for completing the five units of Power of One. Students work independently to accomplish goals in leadership and self-improvement. The girls will be recognized on the national website following the national conference in July (www.fccclainc.org). Pictured are: State Officer, Angelina Harp – Senior at East Forest HS; Tessa Korchak – Junior at East Forest HS; and State Officer, Rachel Beatty – Senior at Warren County Christian School.

post_text: Pictured are students from the Forest Area School District FCCLA Chapters (East and West). These students competed at the State Leadership Conference held at Seven Springs from March 20-22, 2019. All students earned silver(S) and gold (G) medals. Twelve students will be moving on to the National Leadership Conference in Anaheim, CA from June 29-July 5. Students will be doing many fundraisers in the near future, such as a pizza and hoagie sale, car wash, and bake sale. If anyone is interesting in supporting the students financially, please contact Lori Beatty, FCCLA Adviser at either East Forest High School or West Forest High School. Students pictured above in the back row are: Jacob Sorenson (G), Eliana Beatty (G), Jacob Humes (S), Dominic Grubbs (S), Jessica Wagner (S), Telford Kunselman (G), Evan Eisenman (G), Travis Swartz (S). Front row is State Officer, Rachel Beatty (G), Amelia Crouse (G), State Officer, Angelina Harp (S), Madison McFarland (G), Emma McFarland (G), and Tessa Korchak (G).

On Thursday, February 28th, the West Forest Industry Club students toured the HomerWood hardwood floor business in Titusville, and spent the afternoon in Erie touring schools including The Great Lakes Institute of Technology, Toni and Guy, The Erie Institute of Technology, and The Lake Erie College of Osteopathic Medicine. The Industry Club is a club for junior high students, designed to get the students to start thinking about what careers they might be interested in. Before heading back to Tionesta, the students enjoyed a stop at the Get Air trampoline park.

Front row, left to right: Logan Niederriter, Izzy Flick, Tori Brown, Braden Custer, and Colt Price

Back row, left to right: Logan Carll, Ty Brown, Jeff Bayle, Shania Brady, Sam Walter, and Amber Guzzi

post_text: Forest Area School District is now participating in the Amazon Future Engineer program and will receive funding from Amazon to start offering computer science classes to students this Fall. Forest Area will join more than 1,000 high schools across the country currently signed up for Amazon Future Engineer, a national program aimed at making computer science accessible to all students. With more than 1,000 high schools signed up, Amazon Future Engineer will serve tens of thousands of high school students.

post_text:
Forest Area Schools sent 4 teams (2 East Forest, 2 West Forest) to Clarion University on Friday Feb 22 to compete in the area Robotics Championship for PA Rural Robotics Initiative. There were 36 teams in attendance. The top teams in the qualifying matches then formed alliances to compete in the finals (similar to the NCAA March Madness brackets). All four of our teams made it to the Final Rounds. Three made it to the quarterfinals. One team made it to semifinals and then to the final game. West Forest Team A formed an alliance with a VTC team and played against the number 1 ranked alliance of 2 North Clarion teams earning them a spot in the PA Eastern State Championship on March 9, 2019 at Keystone Oaks High School. Come down, root for our area schools and see what it's all about!

Names of the second place alliance members pictured -- West Forest students Mitchell McWilliams, Jacob Flick and Tristen Morrow with VTC students Tyler Seelnacht and Nick Schorr.

post_text: The primary grades at West Forest spent time celebrating the 100th day of school. The classes rotated between stations doing activities associated with 100. Mrs. Fish read to the students stories about the 100th day of school. Mrs.Jaquay had the students build with 100 cups, Mrs. Alex made a 100 piece puzzle and the students decorated the pieces. Our PTO volunteers, Mrs. Lesko and Mrs. Greathouse had the students draw 100 gumballs onto their paper gumball machines, and at the gym stations Mr. Wright and Mrs. Brannon supervised the students completing 100 of the following activities: bean bag toss, dribbling, running ladders, sprints, hula hoops and jump roping.

West Forest Elementary

On Friday, January 11, moms and grandmas came to enjoy a Muffins with Mom celebration in Mrs. Alex's first grade classroom. The students presented their guests with recipes on how to make an awesome mom or an awesome grandma. While there, they enjoyed juice and muffins together. Each student got to paint a small canvas with their guest. Thank you to everyone who attended. First grade had so much fun!
